Creating a circular menu in JavaScript involves several steps. Here’s a basic guide:

### Step 1: HTML Structure
Create a container for your menu items.

```html
<div class="circular-menu">
  <div class="menu-item">Item 1</div>
  <div class="menu-item">Item 2</div>
  <div class="menu-item">Item 3</div>
  <div class="menu-item">Item 4</div>
</div>
```

### Step 2: CSS Styling
Style the circular menu and items to mimic the ping system.

```css
.circular-menu {
  position: relative;
  width: 300px;
  height: 300px;
  border-radius: 50%;
  overflow: hidden;
}

.menu-item {
  position: absolute;
  width: 80px;
  height: 80px;
  border-radius: 50%;
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: center;
  background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.7);
  color: white;
  transition: transform 0.3s;
}

/* Position items in a circle */
.menu-item:nth-child(1) { transform: rotate(0deg) translate(120px) rotate(0deg); }
.menu-item:nth-child(2) { transform: rotate(90deg) translate(120px) rotate(-90deg); }
.menu-item:nth-child(3) { transform: rotate(180deg) translate(120px) rotate(-180deg); }
.menu-item:nth-child(4) { transform: rotate(270deg) translate(120px) rotate(-270deg); }
```

### Step 3: JavaScript Functionality
Add interactivity, such as opening the menu.

```javascript
document.querySelector('.circular-menu').addEventListener('click', function() {
  // Add toggle functionality or animation here
});
```

### Final Notes
- You might want to add animations and more styling for hover effects.
- Consider using a library like jQuery for easier handling of events.
- Enhance interactions with click or hover effects to open/close the menu.

Feel free to expand upon this base to create a functional and visually appealing circular menu!

