Unfortunately, the default JavaScript `confirm` dialog doesn't allow customization of button labels; it always shows "OK" and "Cancel." To achieve custom button labels like "ja" and "nej," you can create a custom modal using HTML and CSS. Here's a simple example:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="da">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Custom Confirm Dialog</title>
    <style>
        #confirmModal {
            display: none;
            position: fixed;
            top: 0;
            left: 0;
            width: 100%;
            height: 100%;
            background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
        }
        .modalContent {
            background: white;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            text-align: center;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div id="confirmModal">
    <div class="modalContent">
        <p>Vil du udskrive fakturaen?</p>
        <button id="yesBtn">Ja</button>
        <button id="noBtn">Nej</button>
    </div>
</div>

<button onclick="showConfirm()">Udskriv faktura</button>

<script>
function showConfirm() {
    document.getElementById('confirmModal').style.display = 'flex';
}

document.getElementById('yesBtn').onclick = function() {
    window.print();
    document.getElementById('confirmModal').style.display = 'none';
};

document.getElementById('noBtn').onclick = function() {
    document.getElementById('confirmModal').style.display = 'none';
};
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

This code creates a custom modal dialog with buttons labeled "Ja" and "Nej." When the user clicks "Ja," it will call the `window.print()` function.

